The paper introduces a new class of games and provides technical results related to optimization, equilibrium, and dynamics. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. Additionally, the paper focuses on networked systems and their impact on social outcomes, which suggests that it may also belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. The paper also discusses potential games and convergence to equilibrium, which suggests that it may belong to the Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category. The technical results involve computational complexity and approximation algorithms, which suggests that it may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the impact of selfish behavior on social outcomes, which suggests that it may also belong to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category.
